Use `null` for optional relation clearing.

```ts
await db.update(app.todos, todoId, {
  projectId: null, // clears optional ref
});
```

`undefined` means "leave unchanged".

Pass accessors, not prebuilt queries.

Svelte
```svelte
<script lang="ts">
  import { QuerySubscription } from "jazz-tools/svelte";
  import { getDb } from "jazz-tools/svelte";
  import { app } from "./schema";

  const projectId = $state<string | null>(null);
  const db = getDb();

  const todosSub = new QuerySubscription(() =>
    projectId ? app.tasks.where({ projectId }) : app.tasks,
  );

  const todos = () => todosSub.current;
</script>
```

Solid
```tsx
import { createSignal } from "solid-js";
import { useAll, useDb } from "jazz-tools/solid";

const [projectId, setProjectId] = createSignal<string | null>(null);
const db = useDb();

const tasks = useAll(() =>
  projectId() ? app.tasks.where({ projectId: projectId() }) : app.tasks,
);
```

For dynamic inputs, this makes the query recompute when `projectId` changes.

Use `batch` when you want independent optimistic writes to appear together in one local grouping.

Use `transaction` when both writes must be staged and only exposed after authority acceptance (e.g. must be globally confirmed together).

```ts
// optimistic grouping
const batch = db.batch((b) => {
  b.insert(app.logs, { message: "A" });
  b.insert(app.logs, { message: "B" });
});
await batch.wait({ tier: "edge" });

// authority-bound atomic pair
const tx = await db.transaction(async (t) => {
  t.update(app.accounts, aId, { balance: fromA });
  t.update(app.accounts, bId, { balance: toB });
});
await tx.wait({ tier: "global" });
```

Define a self-referential optional ref on `employees`.

```ts
import { schema as s } from "jazz-tools";

const schema = {
  employees: s.table({
    name: s.string(),
    managerId: s.ref("employees").optional(), // optional manager relation
  }),
};

export type AppSchema = s.Schema<typeof schema>;
export const app: s.App<AppSchema> = s.defineApp(schema);
```

`managerId` gives forward relation `manager`; reverse relation is derived as `employeesViaManager`.

Use the scalar builders directly on `events`:

```ts
const schema = {
  events: s.table({
    eventAt: s.date(),            // event timestamp
    fingerprint: s.binary(),       // small binary payload/fingerprint
    projectId: s.ref("projects"), // relation to projects
  }),
  projects: s.table({
    name: s.string(),
  }),
};
```

If your installed `jazz-tools` uses a different time or byte type name, keep the same shape and substitute the version-specific builder (`date`/`binary` equivalent), and do not `select()` it out of your query so it is always delivered with the row.

Use Jazz’s conventional tables exactly as `files` and `file_parts` and keep the parent row (e.g. `uploads`) as the access root.

Schema shape:
```ts
const schema = {
  file_parts: s.table({ data: s.bytes() }),
  files: s.table({
    name: s.string().optional(),
    mimeType: s.string(),
    partIds: s.array(s.ref("file_parts")),
    partSizes: s.array(s.int()),
  }),
  uploads: s.table({
    owner_id: s.string(),
    label: s.string(),
    fileId: s.ref("files"),
  }),
};
```

Permissions for private uploads via parent-owned access:
```ts
export default s.definePermissions(app, ({ policy, allowedTo, session }) => {
  policy.uploads.allowRead.where({ owner_id: session.user_id });
  policy.uploads.allowInsert.where({ owner_id: session.user_id });
  policy.uploads.allowUpdate.where({ owner_id: session.user_id });
  policy.uploads.allowDelete.where({ owner_id: session.user_id });

  // helper inserts file/parts before upload row exists
  policy.files.allowInsert.where({});
  policy.file_parts.allowInsert.where({});

  policy.files.allowRead.where(allowedTo.readReferencing(policy.uploads, "fileId"));
  policy.file_parts.allowRead.where(allowedTo.readReferencing(policy.files, "partIds"));
  policy.files.allowDelete.where(allowedTo.deleteReferencing(policy.uploads, "fileId"));
  policy.file_parts.allowDelete.where(allowedTo.deleteReferencing(policy.files, "partIds"));
});
```
This pattern keeps file access private to the owning `uploads` row while allowing helper-managed part creation before parent insert.

Use edge-tier write confirmation when the product requires full durability before continuing:

```ts
const file = await db.createFileFromBlob(uploadRow, blob, { tier: "edge" });
const upload = await db.insert(app.uploads, {
  owner_id: session.user_id,
  label: "Attachment",
  fileId: file.id,
}).wait({ tier: "edge" });
```

Then when reading, request at edge and handle partial local state explicitly:

```ts
try {
  const blob = await db.loadFileAsBlob(app, upload.fileId, { tier: "edge" });
  // render or open
} catch (err) {
  if (err instanceof FileNotFoundError) {
    // file row not visible at this tier
  } else if (err instanceof IncompleteFileDataError) {
    // incomplete/invalid chunk metadata; block UI action, offer retry
  } else {
    throw err;
  }
}
```

`IncompleteFileDataError` can mean `invalid-file-record`, `missing-part`, or `part-size-mismatch`; treat it as a recoverable data-integrity state (retry after syncing/edge read), not a generic fetch failure. If using streams, same handling applies with `loadFileAsStream(..., { tier: "edge" })`.

Delete in dependency order so inherited parent-based permissions still permit child cleanup.

```ts
const upload = await db.one(app.uploads.where({ id: uploadId }), { tier: "edge" });
if (!upload) return;

const file = await db.one(app.files.where({ id: upload.fileId }), { tier: "edge" });
if (file) {
  for (const partId of file.partIds) {
    db.delete(app.file_parts, partId);
  }
  db.delete(app.files, file.id);
}

db.delete(app.uploads, upload.id);
```

Do not delete `uploads` first: inherited `deleteReferencing` can disappear and block part/file cleanup, leaving orphaned chunks. This order is required until automatic cascade cleanup is available.

Build a strict projection layer once and reuse it everywhere.

- Define schema-backed, typed projection structs (`TodoRow`, etc.) and a single decoder that validates:
  - exact value count for the query order,
  - each `Value` variant per column,
  - nullable semantics (`Value::Null` only where allowed).
- Drive every read through `QueryBuilder` so projection order is explicit and fixed.
- Use `client.insert("table", row_input!(...))` and `update(id, vec![...])` for writes; treat batch IDs as authoritative write handles.

Example pattern:
```rust
fn decode_todo(id: ObjectId, values: &[Value]) -> Result<TodoRow, AppError> {
    if values.len() != 3 { return Err(AppError::SchemaMismatch); }
    let title = match &values[0] {
        Value::Text(t) => t.clone(),
        _ => return Err(AppError::TypeMismatch),
    };
    let done = match &values[1] {
        Value::Boolean(b) => *b,
        _ => return Err(AppError::TypeMismatch),
    };
    let description = match &values[2] {
        Value::Null => None,
        Value::Text(t) => Some(t.clone()),
        _ => return Err(AppError::TypeMismatch),
    };
    Ok(TodoRow { id, title, done, description })
}

let rows: Vec<(ObjectId, Vec<Value>)> = client.query(
    QueryBuilder::select("todos").limit(50)
)?;
let parsed: Vec<TodoRow> = rows
    .into_iter()
    .map(|(id, values)| decode_todo(id, &values))
    .collect::<Result<_, _>>()?;
```

Do the same for any handler that needs provenance (`created_by`, `updated_by`, timestamps) by extending the projection and decoder together.

Use a single long-lived process client, then scope it per request:

1. keep one `JazzClient` in app state.
2. authenticate caller (JWT/session), map verified subject to `Session`.
3. derive `let db = client.for_session(session);`.
4. perform reads and writes through `db`.
5. on mutation, call `wait_for_batch(batch_id, DurabilityTier::EdgeServer)` (or `GlobalServer` if required by contract), wrapped in `tokio::time::timeout`.
6. requery through `db` at required tier before response.
7. map failures to HTTP status: auth->401, bad input->400/422, policy-filtered/missing->404, auth/policy reject->403, timeout/disconnect->503/504, decode/schema internal errors->500.

Pattern:
```rust
async fn patch_todo(
    State(app): State<AppState>,
    Path(id): Path<ObjectId>,
    Json(payload): Json<PatchTodo>,
) -> Result<TodoDto, AppError> {
    let session = verify_caller().await?; // caller auth only
    let db = app.client.for_session(session);

    let batch = db.update(
        id,
        vec![("done".into(), Value::Boolean(payload.done))],
    )?;
    let timeout = Duration::from_secs(4);
    tokio::time::timeout(timeout, db.wait_for_batch(batch, DurabilityTier::EdgeServer))
        .await
        .map_err(|_| AppError::GatewayTimeout)??;

    let rows = db.query(QueryBuilder::select("todos").filter_eq("id", id.clone()).limit(1))?;
    let row = decode_todo(id, rows.get(0).map(|r| &r.1).ok_or(AppError::NotFound)?)?;
    Ok(map_to_dto(row))
}
```

If caller writes fail policy-wise, return 403 and do not fall back to a backend/admin client; that bypasses authorship/policy guarantees.
